==English==
===Etymology===
{{webster}}
[[w:Old English language|Old English]][[category:Old English derivations]] chaufen meaning ''to [[warm]]'', [[w:Old French|Old French]][[Category:Old French derivations]] chaufer, [[w:French language|French]][[Category:French derivations]] chauffer, from [[w:Latin|Latin]][[Category:Latin derivations]] calefacere, calfacere, meaning ''to make warm''; calere to be warm + facere to make. See [[Caldron]]. 

===Pronunciation===
*Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-eɪf|-eɪf]]

===Noun===

'''chafe''' (''chafed'', ''chafing'', ''chafes'')

#[[Heat]] excited by [[friction]].
#Injury or wear caused by friction.
#[[Vexation]]; irritation of [[mind]]; [[rage]].

===Verb===

'''to chafe'''

#To excite heat in by friction; to rub in order to stimulate and make warm.
#To excite passion or anger in; to fret; to irritate.
#To fret and wear by rubbing; as, to chafe a cable.
#To rub; to come together so as to wear by rubbing; to wear by friction.
#To be worn by rubbing; as, a cable chafes.
#To have a feeling of vexation; to be vexed; to fret; to be irritated.

